opean languages (English, French, German) as examples of this marginality. Chana Kronfeld counters these dominant models of marginality by looking instead at modernist poetry written in two decentered languages, Hebrew and Yiddish. What results is a bold new model of literary dynamics, one less tied to canonical norms, less limited geographically, and less in danger of universalizing the experience of minority writers. Kronfeld examines the interpenetrations of modernist groupings through examples of Hebrew and Yiddish poetry in Europe, the U.S., and Israel. Her discussions of Amichai, Fogel, Raab, Halpern, Markish, Hofshteyn, and Sutskever will be welcomed by students of modernism in general and Hebrew and Yiddish literatures in particular.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 0aHebrew poetry, ModernxHistory and criticism. 0aMarginality, Social, in literature. 0aYiddish poetryxHistory and criticism. 4aChristianity. 4aJewish studies. 4aJudaism. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / General.2bisacsh  aallusion.  acontraversions critical studies in jewish literature culture and society.  adavid fogel.  adeleuze.  adiaspora.  adiversity.  aguattari.  ahebrew culture.  ahebrew literary history.  ahistorical studies.  ahofshteyn.  aimagist.  ajews.  ajudaism.  aliterary criticism.  aliterary historiography.  aliterary trend.  amarkish.  amodern jewish literature.  amodernism.  amodernist hebrew poetry.  amodernity.  amoyshe leyb halpern.  apoems.  apoetry.  areligion.  areligious literature.  astylistic.  ayehuda amichai.  ayiddish literary history.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of California Press Package Archive Pre-2000z97831106353480 cprintz978052008347940uhttps://doi.org/10.1525/9780520914131?locatt=mode:legacy40uhttps://www.degru